{"altmetric_id":824413,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":46,"citeulike":2,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":27},"f1000":{"unique_users_count":1,"unique_users":["F1000Prime"],"posts_count":1},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":24,"unique_users":["Undertow851RSS","StudentsCloud","knowdrugs","jonlieffmd","K_current","NatRevNeurosci","Cam0092","euroepinomics","neuroscientist","_thePerceiver","LOSSTIME7","PinkProgram1","TAWOP","phynews","AAAS_GR","kristykiwiii","sciencemagazine","sappymonmon","SusyGage","CapitainOmega","JoanmiMmc","Point_Mutation","Truncercila","SusanaDeLeonMD"],"posts_count":26}},"selected_quotes":["Neuron-glia interactions necessary for cerebellum's role in movement #neuroscience","Bergmann glial cells play role in fine motor coordination #neuroscience","In Science: fine motor coordination requires AMPA receptors in Bergmann glial cells (\u00a3)","Bergmann Glial AMPA Receptors Are Required for Fine Motor Control"],"citation":{"abstract":"The impact of glial neurotransmitter receptors in vivo is still elusive. In the cerebellum, Bergmann glial (BG) cells express \u03b1-amino-3-hydroxy-5-methyl-4-isoxazolepropionic acid (AMPA)-type glutamate receptors (AMPARs) composed exclusively of GluA1 and\/or GluA4 subunits. With the use of conditional gene inactivation, we found that the majority of cerebellar GluA1\/A4-type AMPARs are expressed in BG cells. In young mice, deletion of BG AMPARs resulted in retraction of glial appendages from Purkinje cell (PC) synapses, increased amplitude and duration of evoked PC currents, and a delayed formation of glutamatergic synapses. In adult mice, AMPAR inactivation also caused retraction of glial processes. The physiological and structural changes were accompanied by behavioral impairments in fine motor coordination. Thus, BG AMPARs are essential to optimize synaptic integration and cerebellar output function throughout life.","abstract_source":"pubmed","ads_id":"2012Sci...337..749S","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa4df3cf058f610001f6